  • Privacy metadata indicating the level of protection required to safeguard potentially stigmatizing information, which if disclosed without authorization, would present a high risk of harm to an individual's reputation and sense of privacy.*Usage Note:* The level of protection afforded restricted confidential information is dictated by specially protective organizational or jurisdictional privacy policies, including at an authorized individual's request, intended to engender patient trust in providers of sensitive services.Privacy policies mandating additional levels of protection by restricting information access preempt less protective privacy policies when the information is used in the delivery and management of healthcare. May be pre-empted by jurisdictional law (e.g., for public health reporting or emergency treatment).Confidentiality code total order hierarchy: Restricted (R) is less protective than *V*, and subsumes all other protection levels (i.e., *N, M, L, and U*).**Examples:** Includes information that is additionally protected such as sensitive conditions mental health, HIV, substance abuse, domestic violence, child abuse, genetic disease, and reproductive health; or sensitive demographic information such as a patient's standing as an employee or a celebrity. May be used to indicate proprietary or classified information that is not related to an individual (e.g., secret ingredients in a therapeutic substance; or the name of a manufacturer). ( src )

121079 préliminaire Initial images used to establish a beginning condition that is used for comparison over time to look for changes. [Paraphrases NCI-PT (C1442488, UMLS, "Baseline"), which is defined as "An initial measurement that is taken at an early time point to represent a beginning condition, and is used for comparison over time to look for changes. For example, the size of a tumor will be measured before treatment (baseline) and then afterwards to see if the treatment had an effect. A starting point to which things may be compared."]

web dicom.nema.org Include ces codes sont définis dans http://dicom.nema.org/resources/ontology/DCM
Code Display Définition
111636 Dose dans l'air à l'entrée du patient (Kerma dans l'air) Exposure measurement in air at the reference point that does not include back scatter, according to MQCM 1999.
111637 DGM total : Dose Glandulaire Moyenne Total Average Glandular Dose to a single breast accumulated over multiple images.
113722 PDS Total : Produit Dose Surface Total Total calculated Dose Area Product (in the scope of the including report).
113726 PDS de Scopie Total : Produit Dose Surface de Scopie Total Total calculated Dose Area Product applied in Fluoroscopy Modes (in the scope of the including report).
113727 PDS de Graphie Total : Produit Dose Surface de Graphie Total Total calculated Dose Area Product applied in Acquisition Modes (in the scope of the including report).
113730 Temps total de scopie Total accumulated clock time of Fluoroscopy in the scope of the including report (i.e., the sum of the Irradiation Duration values for accumulated fluoroscopy irradiation events).
113731 Nombre total d’images radiographiques Accumulated Count of exposure pulses (single or multi-frame encoded) created from irradiation events performed with high dose (acquisition).
113507 Activité administrée The calculated activity at the Radiopharmaceutical Start Time when the radiopharmaceutical is administered to the patient. The residual activity (i.e., radiopharmaceutical not administered) , if measured, is reflected in the calculated value. The estimated extravasation is not reflected in the calculated value.
113813 PDL Total : Produit Dose Longueur Total The total dose length product for the defined scope of accumulation.
113830 IDSV Moyen : Indice de Dose Scanographique Volumique "Mean CTDIvol" refers to the average value of the CTDIvol associated with this acquisition.
113839 E : Dose efficace Effective dose in mSv.
